  "prompt": "How is cgpa calculated for MS?",
  "response": "CGPA (Cumulative Grade Point Average) for MS (Master of Science) programs is typically calculated as follows:\n\n1. Grade Point System:\n- Each course is assigned a letter grade (A, B, C, etc.)\n- Each letter grade corresponds to a numeric grade point\n- Example: A = 4.0, B = 3.0, C = 2.0\n\n2. Calculation Method:\n- Multiply each course's grade point by its credit hours\n- Sum these weighted grade points\n- Divide by total credit hours attempted\n\n3. Formula:\nCGPA = (Sum of (Grade Points \u00d7 Credit Hours)) \u00f7 Total Credit Hours\n\n4. Example:\nCourse A: 4.0 grade point \u00d7 3 credits\nCourse B: 3.5 grade point \u00d7 4 credits\nCourse C: 3.0 grade point \u00d7 3 credits\n\nTotal weighted points = (4.0 \u00d7 3) + (3.5 \u00d7 4) + (3.0 \u00d7 3)\nTotal credits = 3 + 4 + 3 = 10\nCGPA = Total weighted points \u00f7 Total credits\n\n5. Variations may exist between universities, so always check specific institutional guidelines.",
